 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 38,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import scipy.stats\n",
    "\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "from mpl_toolkits.mplot3d import Axes3D\n",
    "import cmocean as cmo\n",
    "plt.style.use('seaborn')\n",
    "\n",
    "π = np.pi"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Gaussian distributions"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Univariate Gaussian distribution"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The probability density function for the univariate Gaussian distribution is \n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "\\mathcal{N}\\left(x|\\mu, \\sigma^2\\right) = \\frac{1}{\\left(2\\pi \\sigma^2\\right)^{1/2}} \\exp\\left(-\\frac{1}{2\\sigma^2}(x-\\mu)^2 \\right)\n",
    "\\end{equation}\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Multivariate Gaussian distribution"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The probability density function for the $n$-dimensional multivariate Gaussian distribution is \n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "\\mathcal{N}(x|{\\mu}, \\Sigma) = \\frac{1}{\\left(2\\pi\\right)^{N/2}|\\Sigma|^{1/2}} \\exp\\left(- \\frac{1}{2}(x - {\\mu})^T \\,\\Sigma^{-1}({x} - {\\mu}) \\right)\n",
    "\\end{equation}\n",
    "\n",
    "for $x\\in \\mathbf{R}^{n}$, the mean vector $\\mu\\in \\mathbf{R}^{n}$, and the covariance matrix $\\Sigma\\in S_n^+$.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Properties of the covariance matrix $\\Sigma$"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### Symmetry"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "\n",
    "It turns out that the covariance matrix $\\Sigma$ can be taken to be symmetric, without loss of generality. To show this, we first note that any quadratic form of the form $x^T Ax$ is a scalar, hence symmetric with respect to $A$,\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{equation*}\n",
    "x^TAx = \\left(x^T A x\\right)^T = x^T A^T x,\n",
    "\\end{equation*}\n",
    "\n",
    "since any scalar is equal to its own transpose. Second, recall the identity that any matrix can be decomposed into anti-symmetric and symmetric components\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{equation*}\n",
    "A = \\frac{1}{2}\\left(A - A^T\\right) + \\frac{1}{2}\\left(A + A^T\\right).\n",
    "\\end{equation*}\n",
    "\n",
    "Consider the antisymmetric part $A - A^T$. Let $z = (x-\\mu)$.\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{equation*}\n",
    "z^T\\left(A - A^T\\right)z = z^T A z - z^T A^T z = 0\n",
    "\\end{equation*}\n",
    "\n",
    "and the antisymmetric part of the matrix does not contribute to the exponential. Therefore the covariance $\\Sigma$ and the precision $\\Sigma^{-1}$ can be taken as symmetric without any loss of generality.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### Expression in terms of eigenbasis"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 112,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# for purposes of demonstration\n",
    "class MVG(object):\n",
    "    def __init__(self, μ, Σ):\n",
    "        self.N = len(μ)\n",
    "        self.μ, self.Σ = μ, Σ\n",
    "        self.Σ_inv, self.Σ_det = np.linalg.inv(Σ), np.linalg.det(Σ)\n",
    "        self.norml = 1/((2*π)**(self.N/2)*np.sqrt(self.Σ_det))\n",
    "        \n",
    "    def pdf(self, x):\n",
    "        arg = -1/2*(x-self.μ).T @ self.Σ_inv @ (x - self.μ)\n",
    "        pdf = self.norml * np.exp(arg)\n",
    "        return pdf"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 113,
   "metadata": {
    "code_folding": [
     0
    ]
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def grid_eval(X, Y, mvg):\n",
    "    grid_shape = X.shape\n",
    "    for i in range(grid_shape[0]):\n",
    "        for j in range(grid_shape[1]):\n",
    "            x = np.array([X[i,j], Y[i,j]])\n",
    "            Z[i,j] = mvg.pdf(x)\n",
    "    return Z"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "metadata": {
    "code_folding": []
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def plot_gaussian(X, Y, Z):\n",
    "    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(6,3))\n",
    "\n",
    "    ax = fig.add_subplot(121)\n",
    "    ax.contourf(X, Y, Z, levels=8, cmap=cmo.cm.tempo)\n",
    "\n",
    "    ax = fig.add_subplot(122, projection='3d')\n",
    "    ax.plot_surface(X, Y, Z, cmap=cmo.cm.tempo)\n",
    "    plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "metadata": {
    "code_folding": [
     0
    ]
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def view_gaussian(μ, Σ):\n",
    "    mvg = MVG(μ, Σ)\n",
    "    Z = grid_eval(X, Y, mvg)\n",
    "    plot_gaussian(X, Y, Z)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The mean $\\mu$ controls the position of the center of the distribution. The covariance matrix $\\Sigma$ determines the \"shape\" of the distribution."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "Σ = np.eye(2)\n",
    "μ = np.array([0,0])"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "x = np.linspace(-5,5,50)\n",
    "X, Y = np.meshgrid(x,x)\n",
    "Z = np.zeros_like(X)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",

       "<Figure size 432x216 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "view_gaussian(μ, Σ)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 432x216 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "μ = np.array([2.2,2.2])\n",
    "view_gaussian(μ, Σ)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 10,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# create a random covariance matrix\n",
    "#A = np.random.rand(2,2) + 0.2\n",
    "#Σ = A.T @ A"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 101,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "μ = np.array([1, 1])\n",
    "Σ = np.array([[1.1, 0.9],\n",
    "              [0.9 ,1]])"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 102,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 432x216 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "view_gaussian(μ, Σ)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The eigenvectors of the covariance matrix $\\Sigma$ determine the principle axis directions of the multivariate distribution and the egienvalues determine the relative scaling (and hence) shape of the distribution."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 103,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "λ, w = np.linalg.eig(Σ)\n",
    "U = w.T"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 104,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 216x216 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "yi = λ[:,np.newaxis]*U\n",
    "mvg = MVG(μ, Σ)\n",
    "Z = grid_eval(X, Y, mvg)\n",
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,1, figsize=(3,3))\n",
    "ax.contourf(X, Y, Z, levels=15, cmap=cmo.cm.tempo)\n",
    "for i in range(2):\n",
    "    ax.arrow(*μ, yi[i,0], yi[i,1], color='r', head_width=0.15)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Conditional and marginal distributions"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Given a joint Gaussian distribution $\\mathcal{N}\\left(x|\\mu,\\Sigma\\right)$, and precision $\\Lambda \\equiv \\Sigma^{-1}$ and the partition\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{equation*}\n",
    "x = \n",
    "\\begin{pmatrix}\n",
    "x_a \\\\ x_b\n",
    "\\end{pmatrix},\\qquad\n",
    "\\mu = \n",
    "\\begin{pmatrix}\n",
    "\\mu_a \\\\ \\mu_b\n",
    "\\end{pmatrix},\n",
    "\\end{equation*}\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{equation*}\n",
    "\\Sigma = \n",
    "\\begin{pmatrix}\n",
    "\\Sigma_{aa} & \\Sigma_{ab} \\\\\n",
    "\\Sigma_{ba} & \\Sigma_{bb}\n",
    "\\end{pmatrix},\\qquad\n",
    "\\Lambda = \n",
    "\\begin{pmatrix}\n",
    "\\Lambda_{aa} & \\Lambda_{ab} \\\\\n",
    "\\Lambda_{ba} & \\Lambda_{bb}\n",
    "\\end{pmatrix},\n",
    "\\end{equation*}\n",
    "\n",
    "We provide a summary of the results; the derivations are algebra-heavy and appear in the appendix. The idea of all the proofs is to write out a partitioned vector and covariance matrix and expand the qaudratic form in the exponential, comparing like terms.\n",
    "\n",
    "The conditional distribution $p\\left(x_a|x_b\\right)$ is \n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{align}\n",
    "p\\left(x_a|x_b\\right) &= \\mathcal{N}\\left(x| \\mu_{a|b}, \\Lambda_{aa}^{-1}\\right) \\\\\n",
    "\\mu_{a|b} &= \\mu_a - \\Lambda_{aa}^{-1} \\Lambda_{ab} \\left(x_b - \\mu_b\\right)\n",
    "\\end{align}\n",
    "\n",
    "The marginal distribution $p(x_a)$ is\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "p(x_a) = \\mathcal{N}\\left(x_a | \\mu_a, \\Sigma_{aa}\\right)\n",
    "\\end{equation}\n",
    "\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 105,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "xb = -1\n",
    "μa, μb = μ[0], μ[1]\n",
    "Λ = np.linalg.inv(Σ)\n",
    "Λaa, Λab = Λ[0,0], Λ[0,1]\n",
    "μab = μa - 1/Λaa*Λab*(xb - μb) \n",
    "cond = scipy.stats.norm(loc=μab, scale=np.sqrt(1/Λaa))\n",
    "marg = scipy.stats.norm(loc=μa, scale=np.sqrt(Σ[0,0]))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 109,
   "metadata": {
    "code_folding": []
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 504x252 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "mvg = MVG(μ, Σ)\n",
    "Z = grid_eval(X, Y, mvg)\n",
    "\n",
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,2, figsize=(7,3.5))\n",
    "ax[0].contourf(X, Y, Z, levels=15, cmap=cmo.cm.tempo)\n",
    "ax[0].plot(x, np.ones_like(x)*xb)\n",
    "\n",
    "ax[1].plot(x, cond.pdf(x), label=r'$p(x_a|x_b)$')\n",
    "ax[1].plot(x, marg.pdf(x), label=r'$p(x_a)$')\n",
    "plt.legend(); plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Bayes' theorem for Gaussian variables"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Appendix: Derivations"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Maniuplation of Gaussian distributions is usually done up to a normalizing constant and involves algebraically grouping terms in the exponential.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Preliminaries \n",
    "\n",
    "We will make repeated use of the generic form of the quadratic form in the exponential of a multivariate Gaussian distribution, to which we will often compare terms.\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "\\label{eq:gauss_QF}\n",
    "-\\frac{1}{2} (x-\\mu)^T \\Sigma^{-1} (x-\\mu)\n",
    "= -\\frac{1}{2}  x^T \\Sigma^{-1} x + x^T \\Sigma^{-1} \\mu + \\text{const},\n",
    "\\end{equation}\n",
    "\n",
    "as well as the so called 'Elliptic rectification identity' which can identify a mean once we have the quadratic form in the exponential. This is sometimes referred to as \"completing the square\" for a Gaussian distribution.\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "-\\frac{1}{2} x^T A x + x^T v = \n",
    "-\\frac{1}{2} \\left(x - A^{-1}v\\right)^T\n",
    "A \\left(x - A^{-1}v\\right)\n",
    "+ \\frac{1}{2} v^T A^{-1} v.\n",
    "\\end{equation}\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Partitioned Gaussian\n",
    "The joint Gaussian distribution $\\mathcal{N}\\left(x|\\mu,\\Sigma\\right)$, and precision $\\Lambda \\equiv \\Sigma^{-1}$ can be expressed with the partition\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{equation*}\n",
    "x = \n",
    "\\begin{pmatrix}\n",
    "x_a \\\\ x_b\n",
    "\\end{pmatrix},\\qquad\n",
    "\\mu = \n",
    "\\begin{pmatrix}\n",
    "\\mu_a \\\\ \\mu_b\n",
    "\\end{pmatrix},\n",
    "\\end{equation*}\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{equation*}\n",
    "\\Sigma = \n",
    "\\begin{pmatrix}\n",
    "\\Sigma_{aa} & \\Sigma_{ab} \\\\\n",
    "\\Sigma_{ba} & \\Sigma_{bb}\n",
    "\\end{pmatrix},\\qquad\n",
    "\\Lambda = \n",
    "\\begin{pmatrix}\n",
    "\\Lambda_{aa} & \\Lambda_{ab} \\\\\n",
    "\\Lambda_{ba} & \\Lambda_{bb}\n",
    "\\end{pmatrix},\n",
    "\\end{equation*}\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{align}\n",
    "-\\frac{1}{2} \\left(x -\\mu\\right)^T & \\Lambda \\left(x-\\mu\\right) \\\\\n",
    "=&-\\frac{1}{2} \\left(x_a - \\mu_a\\right) \\Lambda_{aa} (x_a - \\mu_a)\n",
    "-\\frac{1}{2} \\left(x_a - \\mu_a\\right) \\Lambda_{ab} (x_b - \\mu_b) \\\\\n",
    "&-\\frac{1}{2} \\left(x_b - \\mu_b\\right) \\Lambda_{ba} (x_a - \\mu_a)\n",
    "-\\frac{1}{2} \\left(x_b - \\mu_b\\right) \\Lambda_{bb} (x_b - \\mu_b)\n",
    "\\label{eq:partitioned_quad}\n",
    "\\end{align}\n",
    "\n",
    "Which will be useful in algebraic manipulation of Gaussian distributions."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Conditional Gaussian distributions"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "\n",
    "A multivariate Gaussian conditioned on some of the components, $p\\left(x_a | x_b\\right)$ is also a multivariate Gaussian distribution, because the joint distribution factors as $p\\left(x_a,x_b\\right) = p\\left(x_a|x_b\\right)p\\left(x_b\\right)$. Therefore the conditional distribution $p\\left(x_a|x_b\\right)$ is a re-normalization of the joint distribution. We are therefore justified in writing \n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{equation*}\n",
    "p\\left(x_a|x_b\\right) = \\mathcal{N}\\left(x_a|\\mu_{a|b}, \\Sigma_{a|b}\\right)\n",
    "\\end{equation*}\n",
    "\n",
    "where it remains to determine the parameters $\\mu_{a|b}$ and $\\Sigma_{a|b}$.\n",
    "\n",
    "We use the quadratic form of the partitioned joint distribution in (\\ref{eq:partitioned_quad}) and inspect the form of all terms involving $x_a$. All other terms in the exponential are constant (since $x_b$ is determined) and affect the normalization only.\n",
    "\n",
    "We have to group all of the $x_a$ terms, using the symmetry of the precision matrix $\\Lambda_{ab} = \\Lambda_{ba}^T$ to write \n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{align*}\n",
    "-\\frac{1}{2} (x-\\mu)^T\\Lambda(x-\\mu)\n",
    "&= \n",
    "-\\frac{1}{2} x_a^T \\Lambda_{aa} x_a + x_a^T \\Lambda_{aa}\\mu_a\n",
    "- x_a^T \\Lambda_{ab} x_b + x_a^T \\Lambda_{ab} \\mu_b + \\text{const}\\\\ \n",
    "&= -\\frac{1}{2} x_a^T \\Lambda_{aa} x_a\n",
    "+ x_a^T\\left(\\Lambda_{aa}\\mu_a + \\Lambda_{ab}(x_b - \\mu_b)\\right) + \\text{const} \\\\\n",
    "&= -\\frac{1}{2} x_a^T \\Lambda_{aa} x_a\n",
    "+ x_a^T \\Lambda_{aa}\\left(\\mu_a + \\Lambda_{aa}^{-1}\\Lambda_{ab}(x_b - \\mu_b)\\right) + \\text{const}. \\\\\n",
    "\\end{align*}\n",
    "\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "By comparing terms with the generic quadratic form associated with a generic multivariate Gaussian,\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{equation*}\n",
    "-\\frac{1}{2}  x^T \\Sigma^{-1} x + x^T \\Sigma^{-1} \\mu + \\text{const},\n",
    "\\end{equation*}\n",
    "\n",
    "by inspection we have that the precision and the mean of the conditional distribution are\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{align}\n",
    "\\Sigma_{a|b}^{-1} &= \\Lambda_{aa} \\\\\n",
    "\\mu_{a|b} &= \\mu_a + \\Lambda_{aa}^{-1}\\Lambda_{ab}(x_b - \\mu_b).\n",
    "\\end{align}\n",
    "\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Marginal Gaussian distributions"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The idea here is to evaluate the marginal distribution by direct integration\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{align}\n",
    "p(x_a) &= \\int_{}^{} p\\left(x_a,x_b\\right) \\,d x_b\\\\\n",
    "&\\propto \\int_{}^{} \\exp(\\text{all terms}) \\,d x_b\\\\\n",
    "&= \\exp\\left(\\text{non-} x_b \\text{ terms}\\right)\n",
    "\\int_{}^{}\\exp \\left( x_b \\text{ terms} \\right) \\,d x_b\n",
    "\\end{align}\n"
   ]
  },
